segments.text: When the bugle for Reveille was played, is that a true story as far as you know?
I don't know.
Is that what's supposed to have happened?
Supposedly, that's why they called it Reveille.
Well, see, I wasn't there when Reveille was blown every morning.
And did Reveille come into classrooms sometimes?
Oh, yeah.
Just in the mess hall, classroom, mess hall, whatever.
And everybody accepted her.
Oh, yeah.
But nobody paid any attention to her.
She wasn't handled like she is now by any means.
Do you remember who took care of her?
Nobody.
In the early days?
Nobody took care of her.
Where did she sleep?
I imagine she went to the dormitories at night to be my guest.
But nobody had anything to say.
She didn't belong to anybody.
She cared for herself.
Religious activities, were there churches, religious activities going on at Northgate?
Yes, yes.
Did you ever attend over there?
I did not, no.
I was never there on the weekend for that time.
Was there a religious emphasis week in the spring?
I think there was, as I remember.
And in terms of religious affiliation, there were plenty of Protestants and Catholics.
Were there some Jewish students, too?
Oh, I'm sure.
I'm sure there were.
And everybody was treated okay?
In fact, I expect my company commander was Jewish.
His name was Lefkoski.
Wouldn't that be Jewish?
It wouldn't be.
Where was he from?
I don't know.
I just saw his picture again a while ago.
I got a more long one out, just reminisced a little.
At the end of your freshman year, did you participate in final review?
Oh, yes.
Yeah.
Describe that.
I guess it was mandatory.
Describe Final Review in those days.
Well, it was hot as hell for one thing.
Well, it was just a plain old review, and I think they did the same thing that I guess they've done forever.
The seniors
watched the last go around and the juniors took over.
I don't think that's changed.
I don't believe.
Did you think you had changed much to move up from being a fish to being a sophomore?
Not nearly as much as the guys lived on campus because, like I told you, I wasn't in any hazing.
But I'll tell you something else I didn't get.
I never got a demerit while I was in A&M.
None.
And then not many of them lived on campus that could ever stand up.
Yeah, that's right, that's right.
So you didn't have to march on the quad.
Bullring.
Bullring, you didn't have to deal with that.
Here comes a lady to...
Come in.
Hello.
Patty, this is Mr. Haskell Monroe.
Good to see you.
Excuse me for not getting up.
It's quite all right.
Where's the cell?
Patsy's brother-in-law was buried this afternoon.
Where were we?
We're talking about things on the campus.
Did you ever go to the campus hospital, to the Quack Shack?
No.
So you don't have... Now, it was located over on the north side of the campus.
It was about, let's see, what's it, in the chapel there now on the campus?
A little north of the chapel, wasn't it?
Yes, just across the street, as I remember from the... Now, the president then was Walton, and he lived in the old house across from Sabeasa.
That burned.
Describe Mr. Walton.
I didn't know anything about him particularly.
And working in the landscape department, I had to work in his garden.
So I used to see him come and go, and he had a black chauffeur.
And he and I communicated a whole lot more than I did with the president.
Now, what did y'all grow in his garden?
Flowers.
Oh, we had pansies and we had...
this border plant that they use still all over campus.
All kinds of flowers.
Where was the flower garden?
Was it in the back of the
to the west side of the house, I believe it was.
What's at that place now where that house burned?
A dormitory.
Oh, is it?
I believe so.
It was a big old two-story house.
And that black boy thought he was some, he couldn't touch a mother's dick.
What did the students and all, what did you all think about President Walton?
I'm not sure that we really thought, had much think about it.
And, Haskell, you know, we were way down on the totem pole at that time.
When Mr. Gilchrist came to be the new dean of engineering,
Did you all see much of him?
No.
Occasionally he would come to some of the engineering classes just to make his appearance.
I got to know him fairly well.
In fact, later on I knew him extremely well being with the highway department.
Describe him in personality.
What kind of man was he?
Oh, pretty headstrong.
very aggressive, very, I would say, very forward thinking.
He was, but practical.
I thought he was very practical.
He had some confrontations with some of the students in certain times.
And he won, didn't he?
Usually, yeah.
Like Rutter did, you know.
Now, physically, Mr. Gilchrist was... Big fella.
Big fella.
And this didn't have anything to do with the campus, but after I became highway district engineer and he was with the state, he attended a lot of functions and I took him to Houston one time
And he was not bragging, but he seemed to like my driving.
So we got down there, and I was going to have to bring him home and then go back.
And Mr. Greer told him, said, Gib, somebody else can take you back to Bryan.
Save Joe having to go back.
He said, Joe will take me.
So Joe took him.
Now, those were tough depression years.
We were just beginning to come out in 36 when I started.
And how important was Franklin Roosevelt in affecting people's attitudes about pulling out of the Depression?
I think he was as well thought of as anybody of that day and time.
We paraded for him one time, too.
Describe that.
Well, we thought we were really doing something, but let me tell you what I did.
I had a camera, and as they brought him up to the reviewing stand, I took his picture, and they took my camera away from me, because he did not want people to know about his... Infantile paralysis.
His leg problem.
His polio.
All right.
How did they get him out of the car up onto the platform?
In a wheelchair.
Okay.
They put him in a chair from the car and had a ramp.
They built a ramp up on there.
As far as you could tell, could he even walk at all?
I didn't see him walk at all, and on the reviewing stand they had a thing for him to hold him up where he could watch as we passed by.
But we thought that was pretty special to review before the President of the United States.
Did anybody attempt any kind of pranks that day?
No.
I know I set my camera.
How big a crowd was there?
There were lots of people there, lots of people.
I think we put on a pretty good parade.
Were there other famous people that came to visit while you were a student?
Well, Russ Morgan.
The big band?
Came to, had a band.
Lucille and I attended at Sabisa Hall.
Kay Kaiser selected the outstanding beauty of the year when he was there.
In fact, his picture's in my annual over there.
We had one or two others that I remember.
They used to have some real functions in that Sabisa Hall.
Did you go to any of those dances?
We did.
We went to Russ Morgan, I remember.
How were girls treated in those days at those dances?
Pretty special.
Most of them, as I said, or a lot of them came, they'd run buses from CIA down there.
And there were some interesting experiences when people wrote a letter to a blind date.
Yeah, I guess so.
What did the young women wear to those dances?
They wear formal long dresses?
Well, it seemed to me like not in it like we call long today.
It seemed to me like most their formal dresses were just below knee.
I know that's what Lucille would wear.
And how did the boys behave?
I think pretty well, I think pretty well.
Occasionally some of them would get them up to the dormitory afterward, which would get them in trouble, you know.
And was there much drinking at the dances?
I just don't remember.
I expect there was, but I don't remember of any brawls or this sort of thing in particular.
And smoking.
What were Aggies smoking in those days?
Well, most of them in my condition wasn't smoking anything.
If there was, they rolled a bullderm.
They didn't have money for cigarettes.
And did, students didn't smoke pipes, did they?
I think there were some pipes I remember that were smoked.
Cigars?
Not many, not many.
Snuff dippers or chewing tobacco?
I expect there were lots of chewing tobacco.
I don't remember much snuff.
In fact, this fellow, Mac New, as I remember, smoked a pipe all the time.
Oh, the faculty members did, yeah.
What did you and your buddies know about drugs?
That was not even talked about that I ever remember.
Didn't know they existed.
I don't guess we did.
I don't ever remember of it.
During those years, were there any places for married students to live on campus?
I don't believe so.
I didn't think there were.
I don't think so.
In fact, there weren't many married students.
Right, right.
Excuse me just a minute.
Hattie, can you handle her all right?
Oh, yeah.
All right.
No project houses or anything.
What was over on that land where College View Apartments would be built?
Was that just more pasture?
I think it must have been because the first things they put out there were some old army barracks.
I think it was right after the war.
That's right.
They moved them in there and students lived in them.
The campus organizations, what did you and your buddies think about the Texas Aggie Band?
Well, it was pretty special, even then.
It had lots of respect.
And Yale leaders?
Yeah, I remember some of the names of the ones that were there.
Brody was one of the ones that I, in fact, I just saw his name in my book there a while ago.
I don't remember them wearing white uniforms like they do now.
I don't know what they wore, but I just don't remember that.
And who did the Aggies want to beat most?
You.
And after that, who would it have been?
Well, they didn't think much of Rice.
You know, Rice was sort of a
high society school.
But we, I guess Texas was really the worst.
I'm trying to think.
And out-of-town football games, you only went to one in Fort Worth?
Fort Worth.
I went to one in Houston.
These were my senior year.
I went to one because we paraded all the way down Main Street in Houston.
And did you go to the game?
I went to the game, yeah.
How did the crowd react on those court trips?
How did they react to Aggies marching?
It was lined up on all sides.
It really was an attraction for them, apparently.
Now, did you go to any basketball games?
No.
Oh, on campus.
At DeWare?
At DeWare Fieldhouse.
Describe going to a game at DeWare Fieldhouse.
Well, it was sort of interesting.
If you shot too high, it hit the roof.
You know, it wasn't like some of them nowadays.
I don't know anything particularly special about it.
Wasn't very big.
Did y'all make a lot of noise?
Oh, yeah.
And it reverberated all over the place, you know, without any insulation.
And the baseball stadium was down next to the railroad?
That's right, right by the side of Kyle Field.
Seats were all tumbledown and in terrible shape.
Hit a ball very hard, they'd go climb over to the football field.
Please share any recollection you have of Colonel Andy.
Let's see.
I don't know of any particular thing.
What was he like as a person?
Well, I didn't have much dealing with him or around him, not being in the corps, you know, and not being in the dormitory.
Was he the corps commandant when you got here, or was he coaching some?
He must have been coaching.
The commandant was a colonel, a colonel...
It was before Colonel Moore.
What was that guy's name?
He was infantry.
Drove a big black Cadillac.
I think that was just my freshman year, and then after him came Colonel Moore.
Did some of those old guys tell you all about what it had been like to be in World War I?
Oh, yeah.
If you ever gave them an opportunity, you know.
If they ever stopped in the shade somewhere, take ten.
Did old former students come back to visit the campus then?
Not significantly that I remember of.
I'll tell you who used to tell those stories was those old sergeants that were in the active army that were assigned to the military department.
They could really tell you big stories.
Let's see, the Yale leaders were special people, weren't they?
Did the singing cadets exist then?
I got a picture of them over there in that thing.
They were there.
I didn't even think about that until I was looking at my annual a while ago.
They were there in 40.
Were you aware then or later that there were any secret fraternities at A&M?
No.
Never heard of such.
Did you ever hitchhike?
Oh, that's the only way you went anywhere.
Describe Aggie hitchhiking.
The main place that they, the two places they had, one was out on 6th to go south.
At Eastgate.
At Eastgate.
And the other one was in Bryan, catacombed across from the courthouse where the health department is now.
There was a church there.
And they're on that corner.
And every time one walked up, he asked, who's the last one?
And he gave them his number, and then you took the next number.
And when they came along and picked somebody off, then you moved up.

but you didn't dare buck the line you got where your life was and I've seen as many as a hundred standing on that corner and Haskell and many of those boys would get out there and hitchhike all day Saturday go as far as they could didn't go anywhere particularly and then turn around Sunday morning or Sunday afternoon and start back just to get away
Did you ever, you personally or anybody you ever hear of, have any bad Aggie hitchhiking?
No, I never heard of that.
Never.
And anybody that came along, if they had any room, they'd pick them up.
But here's another interesting thing.
If somebody came along and he's going to go to Calvert or he's going to go to Hearn, they didn't want to go there because there wasn't anybody stopping at Hearn or Calvert.
They wanted to either go to Waco or Fort Worth or somewhere.
And they didn't have any compunction about turning it down.
They'd just say they'd rather not go to Hearn.
Now, if you were in downtown Bryan and wanted to get a ride back to College Station, where did you go?
I don't remember where that was, but I know they did that.
I suppose they'd stand on any corner and somebody would know if he had a uniform on he was going back to campus.
Did many students go to and from College Station on the train?
Did they catch the train to go home?
Oh, to go home?
Oh, yeah, I'm sure.
Worlds of them did.
In fact, that's the way they'd go to Houston, Dallas, Fort Worth, the ones that had the money.
Most of them hitchhiked.
Where did an airplane land in the 30s in this county?
Where was there a runway?
I don't have any idea.
Because Easterwood didn't exist, and Coulter Field wasn't built yet, was it?
I don't think so.
As far as you know, President Roosevelt came by train.
Oh, yeah.
I know he came by train, because they ran a train ahead of his train.
I know that.
Security.
Did you all listen to his fireside chats, you and your parents and everything?
Yes.
Everybody did.
We had a battery radio out at Wheelock, because it didn't have any electricity.
Oh, they'd gather around.
Did people feel better after they heard President Roosevelt?
I think so.
He had a settling voice.
Let's see.
Who were the famous people
then or later, who were students when you were here?
Who were some of the students who became famous?
Woody Varner was one of them.
Oh, describe Woody.
Woody was the cadet colonel in my senior year.
Oh, make believe I didn't know who he was.
Tell me about Woody Varner.
Derwood T. Varner from Cottonwood, Texas.
Yeah.
Went on up to, what, Kansas or where?
Nebraska.
Nebraska, yeah.
Oh, he was, I think he was well liked by the students.
He was, he was a good leader as far as I'm concerned, I was, could say concerned.
But here again, Haskell not being in the, living in dormitories, I didn't have a lot of personal connection with a lot of those, a lot of those guys.
Physically, what size was he?
I would say he was probably a six foot man, probably would have weighed 160 or 170 or something like this.
Good, trim young man.
Very, very military looking.
Was a good athlete and a good student.
Yeah, I know.
Let's see.
Dick Todd, you overlapped with him.
Oh, I did.
Describe him.
Scatback, that's the best description of him.
He could run through and around more people than you ever did see.
I saw several football games that he was in.
If he could have been on a team like Kimbrough, or one or two of those others later on, he would have been a phenomenal player.
But he was ahead of them.
Now you overlap with John Kimbrough.
Oh, yes.
Describe him.
Oh, he was a horse.
See I was in school his junior year and then through the spring of his senior year and then I went to his games
in the fall of his senior year.
I was over Texas the day that they beat us.
It was a cold, dreary day, and everybody was all uptight about the game, you know.
And this fella Crane.
Jack Crane.
Jack Crane made a touchdown in 60 seconds.
Yep.
And that was the ball game.
Did you go to it?
I was there.
I was there.
I bet Aggies were sick when the game was over, weren't they?
Didn't bother us for the first half, you know.
Oh, we'll come out of it.
But when that game was over, it was terrible.
Lucille had a cousin that was in Texas at the time, and we got her and went to the ball game with her, and we told her, she said, if we win today, we're going to go home with you all.
And I said, well, we'd like to have you go, but there's not much chance you're going home with us.
I tell you, that trip home wasn't very exciting.
As far as you know, was Kimbrough a good student?
I don't know.
Did the athletes go to class then?
Sometimes.
Were there, as far as you know, were there any giveaway grades for athletes?
I expect there were.
I don't know anything about that.
But y'all did?
Something's oughta interesting.
The Blacks, of course, were not very well thought of at that time.
I remember one, see that team always went on the train, out of town ball games.
They went on a game out to California or Utah or somewhere one time.
And Porter was going to lock the, they stayed on the car at night.
He was going to lock the car.
And some of them wasn't in and he told them they couldn't get in.
And they just about ganged him.
They had quite a deal about that.
Let's see, Marion Pugh was on those teams.
He was.
Did you know him then?
Just casual.
Doggy Pugh, I think he called him.
Dookie Pugh.
Dookie Pugh, okay.
Did you know any of the other Bill Connats, sir?
No, there was one that I knew a little bit.
What was his name?
I can't remember his name.
I came in contact with one of them several times.
Let's see, now let's talk about international events.
Do you remember being aware when Germany invaded Poland in the fall of 1940, 1939?
1939, yeah.
How did you hear about it, on the radio?
Yeah, and there was an old Czech man that worked for the landscape department, name was Brin, and he had come from Czechoslovakia.
And he kept up with it, and of course he kept all of us informed about what was happening and why it was all so bad and all that, but people were beginning to worry about it.
It was quite the talk about that time.
Did you and your buddies begin to think that the United States would ever be involved in that war?
Not when I graduated, I guess.
See I graduated in June of 40 and of course Japan was already invading a lot of the southeastern countries over there so they were already on the move.
Germany was on the move and I got I got called active duty in February of 41
I remember that's a year before Pearl Harbor, because I had a commission, got out with the commission, and I got called there.
Roosevelt was beginning to build up the force as he saw it coming, and I got called to duty, so I was on duty a year before Pearl Harbor.
Back to some A&M traditions.
How much did, who paid for your senior ring?
How much did it cost?
Twenty-five dollars.
Twenty-five dollars.
Twenty-five.
Have you ever lost it?
Yes.
Where'd you?
I didn't tell you my story about it?
No.
Oh, I'd love to have a ring story.
Oh, listen.
I was getting ready to go overseas.
It was over in Mississippi.
I had an engineer maintenance company that I was commanded.
We were loading our equipment on the train.
It rained all day.
I was up and down the train supervising the tying down, loading equipment.
It was gravel.
It wasn't any asphalt.
And I was walking along and I saw a ring on the ground.
And I reached down and picked it up.
A&M ring.
I looked inside and it said Joe Hanover and I didn't know I'd lost it.
I think what I'm sure all day with my hand down my fingers swell and I expect I put it on my little finger is what I replay and it probably slipped off but I didn't even know I'd lost it.
And have you, do you have any ring stories about being somewhere far far away
and somebody noticing it?
Everywhere you go.
Everywhere.
That ring is identified...
I went to London back in March a year ago.
I ran into a few people over there that said something about my A&M ring.
Of course, after the war,

I was in Europe nearly a year after the war was over, and of course I went to Paris and I went to Switzerland and Luxembourg and all around the country, and even some of those people over there recognized A&M rings.
Senior boots.
Did you have senior boots?
Mm-hmm.
Where'd you get them?
Still got them.
Where'd you get them?
In Hollick?
Hollick.
How much?
Lucille gave me those boots.
She was working.
How did you feel when you first put on those boots?
Oh, that was great.
And let me tell you what, people that bought boots from Hollick, he kept them shined all year, free of charge.
Now, and I've never asked anybody this, did you meet Mr. Hollick?
I met a Mr. Hollick.
One of them.
Describe the one you met.
Well, he was a typical old fellow that looked like he'd worked hard all his life.
Wanted to talk, you know.
We've got a lot of stories to tell you.
Just wanted to be your friend.
